I tried a quick test and put a vim.print(r1) in https://github.com/neovim/neovim/blob/fa22a78d2a5524839437ad04a4e3ba6ff6633de6/runtime/lua/vim/treesitter/_range.lua#L118 and then opened the _range.lua file again.

With the 64bit version I see this for r1 as a first print
``` 
{0, 0, 0, 4294967295, 4294967295, 4294967295 }
```
while the 32bit version shows:
```
{ 0, 0, 0, -1, -1, -1 }
```

So it indeed looks like an overflow somewhere.

My hunch is that this is the 
```lua
local entire_document_range = {
  {
    0,
    math.huge --[[@as integer]],
  },
}
```
We may need to change this to a sentinel value. Can you check what `math.huge` prints on your system?
